AFRICAN SWINE FEVER - RUSSIA (03): (VOLGOGRAD) SUSPECTED, REQUEST FOR INFORMATION
*********************************************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: Sat 29 Jun 2013
Source: Komsomolskaya Pravda (in Russian, trans. Mod.NR, edited]
http://www.volgograd.kp.ru/online/news/1474722/


ASF [African swine fever] is continuing to destroy swine in the Volgograd region. A new outbreak has been registered in Alekseyevsky district. Swine deaths have been reported in private households and in the swine industrial area. According to the province veterinarian, 2500 swine ere destroyed; the premises where the swine were kept and the vehicles used for their transportation will be disinfected. Hunters are continuing to shoot wild boars that are the source of infection.

The following districts are under threat of ASF: Alekseyevsky, Kumylzhensky, Nekhayevskiy, Novonikolayevsky, Novoanninsky, Uryupinsky, and Serafimovichsky. According to the specialists, the source of infection is in other regions, namely Voronezh and Rostov.

The ASF situation is exacerbated in Central Russia and in the southern parts of the country. 44 foci of the epidemic are currently registered in Russia. in Voronezh for example, domestic, industrial, and wild pigs are infected with ASF.

[Byline: Tatyana Alekseyeva]

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-RUS
<promed-rus@promedmail.org>

[Since the start of the current ASF epizootic in Russia, in September 2009, there have been 99 Russian follow-up reports to the OIE, notifying a total of 260 outbreaks spread over the entire western parts of the Federation.

The total accumulated number of domestic swine in the affected holdings was, reportedly, 360 102, among which 7963 clinical cases, 4995 deaths, 337 335 destroyed animals, and 5147 slaughtered animals. In "wild boars" and "wild animals" (most probably, similarly boars) a total number of 431 cases have been reported.

A summarising map is available at the bottom of the report at http://www.oie.int/wahis_2/temp/reports/en_fup_0000013631_20130618_163110.pdf.

The most recent cases were reported to the OIE on 18 Jun 2013 (follow-up report no 98), involving 17 new outbreaks in the Voronezh and Smolensk regions (see ProMED-mail post no 20130618.1779904). Follow-up report no 99, submitted on 21 Jun 2013, reported the absence of additional outbreaks. The media-derived current outbreak in Volgograd, if officially confirmed, is yet to be notified to the OIE.

A HealthMap/ProMED-mail interactive map of Russia can be seen at http://healthmap.org/r/1rTw. The location of Volgograd oblast in southwestern Russia can be seen on the map at http://www.lib.utexas.edu/maps/commonwealth/russiaaddivisions.jpg and the location of Alekseyevsky district within Volgograd can be seen on the map at http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Volgogradskaya_oblast_Alexeevsky_rayon.png. - Mod.AS]
